Administration of VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany
Control audit report
Foreword
Taxes are the main source of revenue for public budgets.
A focus of the Courts of Auditors" activities should therefore be on the examination of this area.
This applies in particular to VAT fraud.
This alone causes annual tax losses in the European Union of an estimated 100 billion euros1.
Already at the VI EUROSAI Congress 2005 in Bonn, the participants pointed out the need for enhanced cooperation.
This makes it possible for the courts of auditors, for example, to exchange audit approaches and to optimise audit practice.
The value-added tax (VAT) is particularly suitable for cooperation, as it is harmonised within the European Union.
In 2006, for the first time, the courts of auditors of both states examined in parallel in the area of VAT.
The corresponding audit report was published in 2008.
Since the USt fraud is a widespread phenomenon in the European Union, close cooperation between the courts of auditors is needed, so that a comprehensive assessment can be made of whether the measures taken are suitable for effectively dealing with the USt fraud.
The two courts of auditors decided to continue their cooperation and carried out a second parallel audit. Administration of sales tax in the Czech Republic and in the Federal Republic of Germany
1. Introduction
Exam number: (CZ) 09/11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892
Subject of the audit: (CZ) Administration of the USt (D) Bilateral audit with the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic (hereinafter NKÚ), Control audit
The objective of the audit is:
 (CZ) The USt administration and the treatment of selected transactions between entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as CZ) and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter referred to as Germany) should be examined, as well as the procedures applied by the financial authorities in the area of intergovernmental assistance.
 (d) The audit should evaluate how the financial management has implemented the recommendations made by the courts of auditors.
In addition, other test fields linked to the USt should be processed.
The findings should be compared in order to determine whether tax procedures can be optimised.
The audit period was the years 2006 to 2008, including relevant information from the period before the audit period until the conclusion of the audit.
2. Summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel examination
The audit offices of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have agreed on a control audit for the administration of the USt.
During the previous parallel examination, they had uncovered suspected cases of intra-Community transactions,
Which made a re-examination fit for purpose.
On the basis of the audit findings, the two courts of auditors issued recommendations on the management of the USt.
The aim of the inspection was to evaluate how these recommendations were implemented and to investigate the suspected cases.
The audit also looked at other issues, including selected cases of high-risk intra-Community transactions, mutual assistance in the recovery of USt claims and the USt audit of large companies.
The Courts of Auditors found that:
1. Recommendations made on the basis of the previous examination
• Recommendation 1: The rules for the registration of taxable persons should be harmonised within the EU
In the first audit, the courts of auditors compared the registration procedures for the USt in the two states and found differences that caused problems.
The Courts of Auditors therefore recommended harmonising the registration of taxpayers within the EU.
This has also been taken up at EU level.
The draft amendment to Council Regulation No 1798/2003 provides for the extension of existing databases in the EU, including a database with the identification number of USt criminals.
The draft also provided for common rules for the registration of taxable persons and their possible deletion.
The Courts of Auditors expected the Member States to agree, in accordance with their decision in principle, on appropriate rules to remove unreliable entrepreneurs from the USt system as early as possible.
On the final version of the draft, the Member States reached political agreement in ECOFIN.
The above-mentioned common rules are no longer included, and the two courts of auditors regret this.
They still consider such regulations to be important in order to prevent VAT fraud.
• Recommendation 2: Monthly submission of the summary notifications As a result of the first audit, the courts of auditors recommended to the Member States that the summary notifications (ZMs) should be submitted on a monthly basis in the future.
The amounts of intra-Community transactions could then be examined more closely.
Council Directive 2008/117/EC amending Directive 2006/112/EC on the common system of value added tax (VAT) for the purpose of combating tax fraud in intra-Community transactions has reduced the deadline for the levying of VAT to one month.
In the CZ, this requirement was implemented by an amendment to the USt Act, which came into force on 1 January 2010.
In Germany, the implementation did not enter into force until July 1, 2010. Thus, it did not transpose into national law the obligation to supply the ZM on a monthly basis.
• Recommendation 3: Data matching of the USt pre-registrations and the ZM in Germany for more reliable VIES data and proposal to examine the merging of the procedures for USt pre-registrations and ZM. The German financial management has taken up the recommendation made by the Federal Audit Office and set up a working group to work out possible solutions.
The work has not yet been completed.
The Federal Audit Office will monitor further developments.
• Recommendation 4: Exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches for a risk management system at EU level In the course of the first audit, the two courts of auditors agreed that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by one Member State alone.
Successful criteria and elements or approaches of a risk management system must be exchanged and implemented in each EU Member State.
If this does not happen, fraudsters will focus on the Member State with the weakest risk management system.
The Courts of Auditors found that the two Member States apply different risk management systems, which have both strengths and weaknesses.
NKU examined the system of information exchange within the EU - EUROCANET, while the Bundesrechnungshof concentrated on the German participation in the "Platform for Risk Management."
2. Verification of selected intra-Community transactions
During the initial audit, the courts of auditors jointly examined transactions in which it was doubtful whether they had actually been executed or whether they had been explained differently by the taxable persons of the two states in the USt pre-notifications (or USt declarations) or ZM.
The courts of auditors selected nine cases of intra-Community supplies of goods between the CZ and Germany for the inspection.
The examinations by the tax offices of both states had not yet been completed at the conclusion of the first parallel examination.
The audit revealed that the tax procedures for these selected transactions have now been completed, and the respective financial authorities had taken appropriate measures to do so (e.g., subsequent USt determinations or the prevention of pre-tax refunds).
3. Examination of selected, particularly risky intra-Community transactions
The audit also included highly risky intra-EU transactions between taxpayers in the EU covered by the EUROCANET system.
EUROCANET is used to identify high-risk taxpayers.
Member States can participate in this system on a voluntary basis.
The CZ is an active participant in EUROCANET. Germany has a passive status, i.e. it does not participate in the exchange of data within the framework of EUROCANET.
From the point of view of an active participant state, it is unsatisfactory that other Member States refuse to participate actively.
As a result, no information could be obtained about which suppliers with German VAT ID would have been classified as high-risk cases.
In the selected transactions, NKU identified both normal business incidents and those suspected of USt fraud, including carousel fraud.
The FÄ was able to check high-risk transactions only to a limited extent, especially in the case of so-called "missing traders," where an examination of the documents alone is hardly sufficient to prove fraud to the taxpayer.
Suspected carousel fraud in imports and exports
It is advisable for customs and tax authorities to work more closely together in order to be able to monitor the quality of the goods and their actual transport routes within the EU to the final consumer.
Germany and a number of other countries have refused to participate actively in EUROCANET because, in their view, there is not a sufficient legal basis.
The Bundesrechnungshof found that the German financial administration uses other instruments to identify high-risk taxpayers.
However, there is a need for communication and exchange of experience between all EU Member States.
The Council of the EU agreed on a draft regulation,
Created by the EUROFISC.
The experience gained so far with EUROCANET should feed into the planned network for the fight against USt fraud.
4. Mutual assistance in the recovery of claims
Intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of claims is subject to the same European legislation in all Member States.
Requests for intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims in the CZ and Germany will therefore be dealt with in the same way.
Bundesrechnungshof and NKU compared the statistics that both Member States sent to the European Commission for the years 2006 to 2008.
These statistics contained inconsistencies.
The two courts of auditors consider it appropriate to reopen the debate on statistics at EU level in order to avoid any future disagreements.
If this is not done, the statistics cannot be used appropriately for comparisons.
In addition, the statistics should include more information on the USt.
An analysis of detailed data can make it easier for the Commission to support Member States in their efforts to combat USt fraud.
Both courts of auditors believe that Member States with a low recovery rate should strive to achieve at least the average recovery rate.
The Commission should support the Member States in this, if they so wish.
5th USt test for large companies
The courts of auditors analysed the legal situation with regard to the USt examination of large companies in both states.
In addition, they collected information from the financial authorities with a questionnaire, which they considered important in this context.
It became clear that the situation in both states is different.
The CZ has a system for selecting risky cases that includes a large amount of relevant data (including information on USt audits, balance sheet data and profit and loss accounts).
The USt control can thus be effectively controlled and analysed as a whole.
A special financial office for large companies is to be set up in 2012.
Germany does not yet have a comparable system, which makes it difficult to control and analyse the USt control as a whole.
The German financial administration concentrates more on the selection of relevant individual cases and relies in particular on data from the USt pre-registrations or USt declarations and the ZM.
Various risk management components, which are to be improved, support the evaluation of this data.
