4. Examination of the management of sales tax in selected areas
4.1 Implementation of the recommendations of the first joint audit
4.1.1 Implementation of the recommendations in the Czech Republic
Recommendation 1
Harmonisation of the conditions for registration of taxable persons within the EU Supported
In response to the results of the first audit, the Czech Court of Auditors recommended that the requirements for VAT registration be adjusted and that new rules be introduced for the deletion of registration in the CZ.
These amended rules should more effectively reduce the risk of possible tax evasion.
In certain cases, it was found that the tax authorities did not delete the registration of taxable persons if they did not comply with their obligations under Czech law No. 235/2004 (hereinafter referred to as the "U.S. Law").
So far, the Czech Ministry of Finance has not submitted an amendment to require the FEA to be cancelled if taxpayers repeatedly fail to file USt declarations.
Under the Czech VAT Act, the FA may ex officio cancel the registration of a taxable person if (a) the taxable person has not made transactions for 12 consecutive months and has not informed the FA of the reasons for doing so; (b) the taxable person has not fulfilled his obligations under the VAT Act; (c) the taxable person no longer fulfils the conditions for tax liability.
The first examination showed that, in view of the existing legal situation, the Prague 1 FA would have to delete the USt registration of "foreign taxable persons"3 with effect from 31 January of the following calendar year, if they were not obliged to register and pay USt in the current calendar year.
The Prague 1 FA often did not delete the USt registration of these taxpayers because the relevant provision of the deadline could not be adequately implemented in practice.
The problem was solved by the amendment of the USt law, which came into force on 1 January 2009.
Accordingly, the FA has the power to delete the registration of a foreign taxable person if, in the previous calendar year, he has not provided taxable or exempt supplies of goods or services with the right to deduct.
Recommendation 2
Monthly fee of the ZM
On the basis of the initial audit, the courts of auditors recommended the introduction of the monthly levy on ZM.
The Council Directive, which reduced the rate of return for the ZM to one month, was implemented in the CZ by the USt Act, which entered into force on 1 January 2010.
The ZM must now be handed over electronically.
In addition, a ZM must be provided if services, the place of performance of which is to be determined in accordance with § 9 (1) of the USt Act, are provided for a person registered in a Member State other than that subject to VAT.
The condition is that the recipient is obliged to declare and pay the VAT on these services, as required by Council Directive 2008/8/EC amending Directive 2006/112/EC as regards the place of the service.
Recommendation 3
Comparison of the data of the USt pre-registration and the ZM to increase the reliability of the VIES data This recommendation related to the German financial management.
In its ATIS4 system, the Czech financial administration automatically balances the data on intra-Community transactions from the USt declarations and the ZM.
Recommendation 4
Exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches for a risk management system at EU level
The proper collection of VAT is a sine qua non for the proper functioning of the EU's internal market.
That is why the fight against USt fraud is of primary interest and has received considerable attention in recent years.
The importance of this is demonstrated, among other things, by an investigation published by the European Commission in October 2009.
In it, an external expert estimated the loss of USt for the 25 Member States between 2000 and 2006. According to the analysis of the available data, the tax loss for the said period was estimated at between 90 and 113 billion euros, based on the fact that the EU-25 loses an average of 12% of the value added tax due to them each year.
The estimated tax loss for the CZ in 2006 was 18%.
The first audit found that a Member State cannot develop an effective risk management system (RMS) on its own.
Successful criteria, components or approaches for a RMS must be exchanged and implemented in each Member State.
In relation to the RMS, the Czech Court of Auditors examined the system for the exchange of information within the EU (EUROCANET).
For this purpose, risky intra-Community transactions carried out by taxpayers within the EU and recorded in EUROCANET were selected (see Chapter 4.3).
The EUROFISC network aims to optimise mutual assistance in tax matters and to combat USt fraud more effectively, and to improve cooperation between the competent authorities in order to detect fraud as early as possible.
Later, EUROFISC could be used as a tool to estimate the risk potential for intra-Community transactions.
The ECOFIN Council6 already approved EUROFISC on 7 October 2008 and at the same time adopted the principles for the functioning of the system.
EUROCANET, developed by the Belgian financial management in cooperation with the other Member States and with the support of the European Commission and OLAF7, serves as a model for EUROFISC.
The purpose of the system is to detect risky transactions and identify entrepreneurs involved in organised USt fraud.
