4.2 Verification of selected intra-Community transactions
The first audit carried out a joint investigation into transactions where there were doubts as to whether they had actually been carried out or whether discrepancies had been found in the notifications of taxable persons in both Member States.
The two courts of auditors selected nine cases of intra-Community supplies of goods between the CZ and Germany for the control examination, where the tax examination by the FÄ of the Member State concerned had not yet been completed at the time of the previous joint examination.
1) 
In the first quarter of 2005, a Czech taxpayer purchased goods worth 22,686 euros from a German taxpayer.
The Czech taxpayer did not declare the acquisition in his USt statement, while the German taxpayer did not have an USt identification number, but only a tax number for intra-German transactions.
By means of international assistance pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, the competent Czech FA had received information that, under German VAT law, the supplier of intra-Community goods does not need an USt identification number in order to benefit from the exemption of intra-Community supplies of goods.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors showed that, according to the audit of the competent Czech FA, the Czech taxpayer submitted an additional USt statement declaring the purchase of goods of the above value and at the same time asserting his right to deduct the same amount of VAT.
2) 
A Czech taxpayer is said to have purchased Euro12,561 worth of goods from a German taxpayer in the fourth quarter of 2004.
However, he said he did not purchase the goods and therefore did not explain them in his USt statement.
The German financial management, citing a provision of Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, refused to process the request because the turnover linked to the acquisition did not exceed the threshold of 15 000 euros.
As the Czech FA was unable to obtain documents, the tax audit was inconclusive and the original tax fix was in place.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors showed that the Czech FA from Germany received two spontaneous reports in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, according to which the German taxpayer had invoiced the relevant goods to a Slovak addressee.
The Czech taxpayer acquired the goods from the Slovak taxpayer and announced the acquisition in its regular VAT declaration for the month of October 2004.
3) 
A Czech taxpayer is said to have purchased a car worth 48,500 euros from a German taxpayer in the fourth quarter of 2004.
However, he did not declare an intra-Community acquisition.
In addition, he had not issued an USt statement since August 2004, which is why the FA set the USt at CZK 0 for the quarter in question.
On the basis of information provided by Germany in the course of the international exchange of information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, the FA asked the taxpayer in March 2007 to file a subsequent tax return, which the taxpayer omitted.
The inspection found that in 2007 the FA had carried out further examinations in this tax case, finding that the car in question had been sold by the taxpayer to a second-hand car dealer in the CZ.
The Czech FA imposed a predisposition for the tax period of December 2004, setting additional taxes of CZK 295 379 for the purchase and resale of goods from another Member State.
The competent Czech court decided to open insolvency proceedings on the assets of the Czech taxpayer; an insolvency administrator was appointed.
In the absence of significant assets, the outstanding tax liability is likely to be irrecoverable.
4) 
In the fourth quarter of 2004 and in the first quarter of 2005, a Czech taxpayer is said to have delivered new vehicles (cars) worth a total of 198 167 euros to Germany.
In response to a request for information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, it was stated that tax proceedings were pending against the German taxpayer in Germany.
The audit carried out by the Bundesrechnungshof showed that, at the end of the proceedings, there was evidence that the German taxpayer was involved in fraud.
The intra-Community acquisition of goods was subject to income tax in the amount of EUR 182 424 (for 2004) and EUR 369 690 (for 2005).
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors revealed that the Czech taxpayer was involved in carousel fraud involving new vehicles.
On the basis of information provided by the German tax administration, a tax audit of the Czech taxpayer took place for the tax periods of April, May and June 2005.
On the basis of the audit findings and the information from the international exchange of information, the FA fixed an additional USt of 703 031 CZK for May 2005 and 726 551 CZK for June 2005.
5) 
Czech taxpayer A is said to have purchased a machine worth a total of 58 000 euros from a German taxpayer in February 2005.
In the third quarter of 2004, the German taxpayer reportedly supplied the Czech taxpayer B with a machine worth 88,027 euros. B, however, denied the acquisition.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors showed that B had purchased the machine from a German company with a branch in the CZ.
Czech taxpayer A did not indicate the purchase of the goods from the above-mentioned German taxpayer in its USt statement.
The German FA's response to a request for information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003 showed that the German taxpayer had not made an intra-Community delivery of a machine worth 58 000 euros, but a delivery within the CZ.
In the inspection, the Bundesrechnungshof found that the intra-Community delivery of the machine was classified as a domestic delivery after the completion of an audit and the USt exemption was subsequently refused.
6) 
In the third quarter of 2004, a German taxpayer reportedly delivered goods worth 11,600 euros to a Czech taxpayer.
The goods were purchased and later sold in Germany, i.e. in 2005.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors showed that the Czech FA had made its assessment on the basis of a supplementary USt statement, which improperly showed acquisitions from another Member State, including purchases in the above amount.
The Bundesrechnungshof found that after receiving a reply to a request for information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, the German FA corrected the VAT declaration of the German taxpayer and set an additional amount of EUR 1 600.
Due to the resale of the goods in Germany and the corresponding USt assessment there, an audit is ongoing.
The ZM of the German taxpayer has not been corrected so far, as in Germany only the taxpayer who has surrendered the ZM can correct it.
7) 
The competent Czech FA received a request for information from the German tax administration in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003 on the issue of the purchase of a car worth 47,400 euros by a Czech taxpayer in February 2005.
After an audit for the 2005 tax period, the Czech FA fixed the tax liability of the Czech taxpayer at CZK 0 and informed the German FA that it could not confirm the acquisition of the car by the Czech taxpayer.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors showed that the registration of the Czech taxpayer had been cancelled because he had not complied with his tax obligations.
The Czech FA had sent the documents to the Czech police.
The German taxpayer has so far not corrected his information in the ZM, but has appealed against the tax ruling.
8) 
According to MIAS10, between the third quarter of 2004 and the first quarter of 2005, a German taxpayer supplied a Czech taxable person with a total value of EUR 33 205, which he did not declare to be an intra-Community acquisition.
The audit by the Czech Court of Auditors found that the Czech FA investigated the reasons for the disagreements.
The Czech taxpayer repeatedly issued subsequent USt statements for the first quarter of 2005.
However, the Czech FA was unable to clarify the difference in the amount of CZK 134 273 in the third quarter of 2004 to the first quarter of 2005, on the grounds that sales for individual quarters could not be accurately allocated, and accepted the USt statements made.
9) 
In the third quarter of 2004, a German taxpayer had delivered goods to a Czech taxpayer worth EUR 46 854.
For the same period, the Czech taxpayer declared the intra-Community acquisition of goods worth only 14 856 euros.
As part of the intergovernmental exchange of information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, the Czech FA reviewed the actual value of the delivery.
With the German answer to this question, three invoices were sent which showed a total value of the delivered goods of EUR 31 998, i.e. an amount equal to the difference between the acquisition declared by the Czech taxpayer and the VIES data.
According to the results of the audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors, the Czech taxpayer, after repeated reminders from the FA, submitted an ex-post statement in January 2007 for the July 2004 tax period.
With this statement, the taxpayer simultaneously asserted his right to deduct, and his tax liability for the tax period in question remained unchanged.
The audit confirmed that most of the tax procedures relating to the transactions selected for the audit had been completed and that the financial authorities in the CZ and Germany had taken appropriate measures (e.g., subsequent USt determinations or prevention of pre-tax refunds).
4.3 Examination of selected cases of risky intra-Community transactions
4.3.1 Findings in the Czech Republic
EUROCANET can be an important source of information to identify high-risk taxpayers in the Member State of acquisition.
In the CZ, the early warning information obtained from EUROCANET is checked by the competent FA with the purchasers.
Since the first quarter of 2008, the CZ has included in the EUROCANET system information on transactions and taxable suppliers that are considered risky.
Nine Czech taxpayers were selected for the audit,
Which had been entered into the EUROCANET by the financial administrations of other Member States, either as suppliers or acquirers.
