Since the German financial administration did not participate in the exchange of data via EUROCANET, it was not possible to determine whether suppliers with a German VAT identification number were classified as risk-prone by the German financial administration.
The audit found both normal business incidents and those suspected of carousel fraud or other USt fraud.
In the cases in question, the FÄ exchanged information in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003,
For example:
• The FÄ did not detect any suspicion of risky transactions when examining the early warning information.
The taxpayers concerned were constantly monitored because their data was stored in EUROCANET.
• In carrying out checks on risky transactions, the FÄ failed to prove, on the basis of the accounting documents submitted, breaches of the rules for calculating the tax base and VAT, even though they found discrepancies in the transport and storage of the goods or revealed business relationships with letterbox companies from other Member States.
• The review of individual business transactions was complicated because certain taxable persons did not cooperate with the FÄ and could not be contacted.
The competent authorities reviewed most of the risky taxable persons and transactions mentioned in EUROCANET's early warning reports.
However, their options for checking risky transactions, especially so-called "missing traders" are limited.
In particular, a mere examination of the documents can hardly prove that the taxpayer is acting fraudulently.
Stricter requirements for the registration of taxable persons for purposes of VAT and greater flexibility in the deletion of registrations would help to combat USt fraud.
Taxpayers involved in fraudulent carousel transactions can register for USt purposes in order to feign fictitious deliveries of goods across the EU or to issue formally correct tax receipts to other taxable persons, with which they then make unjustified claims for deductions.
In the case of suspected carousel fraud in connection with imports and exports, it is advisable for customs and tax authorities to work more closely together in order to be able to trace the nature of the goods and their actual transport routes within the EU to the final consumer.
Member States may participate in EUROCANET on a voluntary basis.
The fact that three large Member States (Germany, Italy and the United Kingdom) did not participate was considered by the European Parliament at the end of 200811 as a weakness of the system, which should be remedied by setting up an EUROFISC network with compulsory participation.
4.3.2 Findings in Germany
The Bundesrechnungshof evaluated the data available at the Federal Central Tax Office, including those from EUROCANET.
They served as a basis for the selection of six German taxpayers whose files were reviewed.
Both Germany and a number of other countries refused to participate actively in EUROCANET.
That is why Germany has a passive status, i.e. it does not send data to Brussels itself, but is only the recipient of EUROCANET data.
This is justified by the fact that "from the point of view of the Federal Government
No unquestionable legal basis [existed] that would allow the tax secrecy existing in Germany to be broken.
In addition, the Federal Government does not have reliable information on how information sent by the Member States is processed within the framework of EUROCANET."12 Since October 2007, the Federal Central Tax Office has been evaluating the EUROCANET data and transmitting it to the federal and state tax authorities on the basis of a coordinated procedure.
The German tax authorities receive control notifications on the direct business relations of the taxable persons registered in EUROCANET with companies from other EU countries.
However, the German FA does not receive any information as to whether the company from the aforementioned other EU Member State has business relations with a company established in another Member State, which is also linked to the German company from the control notification.
4.3.3 Evaluation
The CZ is an active participant in EUROCANET, while Germany has only a passive status.
From the point of view of an active participant, it is unsatisfactory that other Member States refuse to participate actively.
Accordingly, the examination in this area had to be carried out in different ways.
However, there were no significant differences in the success of the detection of USt fraud. The reason for this is that EUROCANET is only one component of the risk management system.
However, the financial authorities of both countries have a variety of other tools to detect fraudulent transactions, but it is still necessary to develop a comprehensive risk management system within the EU.
The Council of the European Union agreed on a draft regulation 13, which created EUROFISC, a network for combating USt fraud.
The experience gained so far with EUROCANET should be shared by the Member States at European level and integrated into this network.
