4.4 Mutual assistance in the recovery of claims
4.4.1 Inter-governmental assistance in the recovery of claims in the Czech Republic
The legislation on intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of certain claims in the EU is essentially based on:
Council Directive 76/308/EEC on mutual assistance for the recovery of claims relating to measures forming part of the financing system of the European Agricultural Guidance and Guarantee Fund, as well as levies and customs duties;
Council Directive 2001/44/EC amending Council Directive 76/308/EEC on mutual assistance for the recovery of claims relating to measures forming part of the financing system of the European Agricultural Guidance and Guarantee Fund, as well as levies and customs duties and VAT and certain excise duties; and
Commission Directive 2002/94/EC laying down detailed rules for the implementation of certain articles of Directive 76/308/EEC on mutual assistance in the recovery of claims relating to certain levies, duties, taxes and other measures.
The CZ implemented Council Directive 76/308/EEC by Law No 252/2000 on intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of certain claims.
After the adoption of Council Directive 2001/44/EC, it also had to be transposed into Czech law, and at the same time the aforementioned law had to be amended.
In this context, the legislative amendment No 191/2004 concerning intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of certain claims was adopted.
A new key piece of legislation was adopted by Commission Regulation (EC) No 1179/2008 of 28 November 2008.
The annexes to this regulation contain new application forms to be used from 1 January 2009, the regulation also makes electronic transmission mandatory and requires the requesting authority to certify the conformity of all documents sent to the original.
The main principles of international mutual assistance for the recovery of claims are:
1. The principle of reciprocity applies;
2. Mutual assistance must always be provided on request and in compliance with all conditions;
3. The mutual assistance does not extend to claims which are considered to be criminal sanctions in the requested State;
4. the procedure of intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of claims must be carried out in accordance with the national law of the requested State;
5. In the recovery procedure, foreign claims do not take precedence over domestic claims;
6. The mutual assistance shall be provided only for the recovery of uncontested claims;
7. The principle of absorption applies: the requesting State must use all the means at its disposal under national law to recover the claim.
Law No 191/2004 provides for three forms of mutual assistance: the provision of information, the notification of legal acts and the actual recovery.
Procedures for outgoing requests to other EU member states
The competent FA shall transmit the request for information, the request for notification of legal acts or the request for recovery, together with the relevant documents, electronically to the CZ Ministry of Finance via the relevant financial directorate.
The Ministry of Finance of the CZ arranges the translation of the request into the language in question, scans it with all facilities and sends it via the communication network or the common interface CCN/CSI to the competent financial authority of the state in question.
A request for recovery assistance must meet the following requirement: the claim must exceed EUR 1 500 and must not be older than five years.
The requested authority may refuse recovery if the requirements are not met.
Procedures for incoming requests from other Member States
The CZ Ministry of Finance must confirm receipt of requests from other Member States as soon as possible, at the latest within seven days.
If it decides not to grant the request, it must inform the requesting authority of the reasons for the refusal, specifying the specific provisions of the directive on which it is based.
The corresponding notification must be sent no later than three months after the date of receipt of the confirmation of the request.
Upon receipt of the request, the Ministry of Finance will examine whether the request meets all legal requirements.
If the request for recovery is granted, the FA will have to determine, among other things, the debtor's assets, e.g., by extracts from the land register, information on existing bank accounts and registration of vehicles with the registration office.
After six months from the date of receipt of the receipt of the request, the Ministry of Finance of the CZ shall inform the requesting authority of the outcome of the investigation.
The requesting authority must also be informed if the taxable persons concerned are not available and the claim cannot therefore be recovered.
All sums successfully recovered must be transferred to the requesting authority within one month of recovery.
The Czech FA, which handles the recovery, can agree on the claim hours or instalments with the consent of the requesting state.
The interest or default surcharges imposed on the debtor for the period of delay pursuant to Law No. 337/1992 on the management of taxes and fees
Stand by the requesting state.
In particular, in 2006 and 2007, the CZ's Ministry of Finance delayed sending the relevant FA the recovery requests received.
The same applies to the forwarding of requests for recovery made by the Czech authorities to the competent authority in the requested state.
The audit found that the Ministry of Finance had breached the law on intergovernmental assistance for the recovery of claims, failing to inform the competent authority of the requesting Member State of the state of the recovery procedure within six months of confirmation of the receipt of the request.
The situation has improved since 2008.
Statistical data
In accordance with Section 13 (4) of Law 191/2004, the Ministry of Finance of the CZ prepares statistics for the European Commission up to 15 March each year. This includes the number of requests for information, notification of legal acts and recovery, including the amount of claims received in the previous year.
On the basis of the data provided by the Member States, the European Commission prepares its report to the Council and the European Parliament on the application of the provisions on mutual assistance in the recovery of claims.
The audit revealed that in 2008 the CZ's Ministry of Finance gave the claims by 5,250,000 euros too low, due to the incorrect indication of the amount of an USt claim submitted in 2008 (caused by the postponement of a decimal point in the conversion of the Czech crowns" claim into euros).
The mistake was subsequently reflected in the European Commission's statistics.
