4.4.4 Comparison and evaluation
In the case of recovery, the requirements of EU law apply to all EU Member States for intergovernmental assistance.
The procedures for processing requests are therefore similar in the CZ and Germany.
Bundesrechungshof and NKÚ have compared the statistics that the two Member States submitted to the European Commission for the years 2006 to 2008.
In the process, disagreements emerged.
In its 200620 report, the European Commission recommended that Member States draw up their statistics with greater care.
In 200921, the Commission concluded that, despite a greater number of requests for assistance, the discrepancies in the statistics have decreased.
Both courts of auditors believe that a renewed discussion at EU level on the statistics would be useful in order to avoid the remaining discrepancies in the future.
If this does not happen, the statistics are conditionally meaningful and cannot be used for comparisons.
In addition, the Courts of Auditors consider that the statistics should indicate both the annual number of requests and the type of claims (e.g., VAT, income tax) and the amount of amounts recovered per Member State.
Through a more detailed analysis of the statistics provided by the Member States, the Commission could assist Member States in assessing their measures to combat USt fraud.
Since the recovery rate can be calculated per Member State, the courts of auditors argue that the Member States with a low quota should at least aim for the average recovery rate within the EU.
At the request of a Member State, the Commission could play an active role in this.
The foreign recovery requests received by the CZ Ministry of Finance were delayed to the competent authorities, especially in the years 2006 and 2007.
The same applies to the requests for recovery made by the Czech authorities.
The audit found that the Czech Ministry of Finance violated Act 191/2004 on intergovernmental recovery assistance in so far as it did not inform the competent authority of the requesting Member State of the progress of recovery measures within the six-month period from receipt of the request.
4.5 Value Added Tax Examination for Large Businesses
4.5.1 Value Added Tax Examination for Large Companies in the Czech Republic
Background
The tax procedure for large companies is subject to the same rules that apply to other taxable persons.
The examination of large companies is regulated by Czech Law No. 337/1992, the "Tax and Fee Management Act."
The Czech Ministry of Finance defines large companies as natural persons who have set up a business or legal entities which have been set up to operate a business and whose net turnover for the relevant tax period is at least CZK 2 billion according to the income or corporation tax declaration.
The taxable person is classified as a large company on the basis of the turnover level according to the income or corporation tax declaration during the respective tax period; for the first time for the year 2003.
A natural or legal person will no longer be held as a large company for the purpose of taxing sales if, in three consecutive assessment periods, their net turnover in the tax period is less than CZK 2 billion. The period begins at the end of the tax period, for which the conditions were met for the first time in accordance with the tax return.
A taxable person can only be removed from the list of large companies if at least one type of tax has been examined in advance for a period of taxation.
By the end of 2009, all large companies were audited at least every five years.
Since 2010, taxable persons have to be assessed in writing at least every two years, and the subsequent control measures are intended to eliminate the tax risks and their negative effects on the proper tax establishment and collection.
The examinations by the FEA should focus on at least one type of tax; they usually include several periods of taxation.
The large tax-paying companies were audited by the special audit bodies or audit services of the competent FÄ set up at a total of 13 FÄ.
A special audit office carried out audits in its local area of responsibility in accordance with the requirements of the head of the financial directorate.
In addition, it also examined:
Tax payers with unusual and special business activities, and
Those whose examination required a high level of expertise and time.
It also examines taxable persons with complex location distribution and organisational structure,
Taxpayers suspected of large-scale tax evasion
As well as tax payers belonging to chains and networks suspected of large-scale tax evasion and unwarranted deductions.
Information on the number of examinations carried out by the special examination bodies of the FÄ and the additional tax results of these examinations are shown in Table No. 3.
The Czech Ministry of Finance has submitted a proposal to amend Law No 531/1990 for the regional tax authorities. In particular, it is proposed to establish a special tax office with national jurisdiction for selected taxpayers (legal persons established for the purpose of economic activity, with a turnover of at least CZK 2 billion).
4.5.2 Value Added Tax Examination for Large Companies in Germany
Background
The USt examination of large companies is not particularly regulated in Germany. Audits are subject to the general regulations • the Tax Regulations (AO), • the Financial Administration Act (FVG) and • the Auditing Regulations (BpO).
There are also work aids.
Order of taxation
The provisions of §§ 193 to 203 AO "section 4 - external examination" contain, in particular, rules for the admissibility of an external examination and its factual scope, the distribution of responsibilities, the form and content of the examination announcement, the principles of the examination, the duty of participation of the taxpayer and the requirements for final interviews as well as for the transmission of the examination report.
External audits are carried out by the competent authorities (§ 195 AO).
According to § 5 paragraph 1 no. 1 in connection with § 19, it is the responsibility of the Federal Central Tax Office to participate in external audits of the FÄ.
The nature and extent of this participation will be agreed between the authorities involved.
In addition, the Federal Central Tax Office may require certain companies it has designated to be audited at a certain point in time.
In this case, it can lay down rules for the external audit of these taxpayers.
In accordance with Article 108, paragraph 7 of the Basic Law, the Examination Regulation (BpO 2000) was adopted with the approval of the Federal Council.
It applies to external audits by the state financial authorities and the Federal Central Tax Office.
According to § 3 BpO, companies are regularly classified in size classes.
Large companies must undergo a follow-up examination (Ziff. 4.2 BpO).
In accordance with section 33.1 of the BpO, each competent financial authority shall keep a list of companies within the meaning of the regulation.
Working aid for the administration
In addition, the following working aids have been issued for the administration:
• "Unified Handbook for the USt Special Examination";
• Sales Tax-Country Online - USLO (= dialogue system in the intra-Community USt control procedure) with guidance on the use of the data contained in the VIES on intra-Community business relations;
• Work aids for difficult and special situations.
• Central database for the storage and evaluation of USt fraud cases and the development of risk profiles -ZAUBER;
Taxable persons are classified in size classes based on criteria such as turnover and profit, with limits varying according to the type of business.
The figures are published by the Federal Ministry of Finance.
The values are reviewed every three years and set for the following three years.
The number of companies - not just large companies - is regularly recorded (last cut-off date: 1 January 2010).
In general, large companies must be thoroughly audited.
The tests are announced and usually extend to the USt,
In other words, the audit covers all relevant taxes, namely income tax, corporation tax, business tax and VAT.
The value-added tax can be checked either by company auditors or by USt special auditors.
The practice varies and depends on the administrative structure of the individual countries.
The number of tax periods covered by an audit generally fluctuates between three and five years.
The BpO 2000 is based on three years.
All taxes that a company has been subject to are subject to the audit.
